SIMPLE: inadvertency
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Inadvertency
<hw>In`ad*vert"en*cy</hw>
<pr>(?)</pr>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>-cies</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr></plu>,
}</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>inadvertance</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The quality of being inadvertent; lack of
heedfulness or attentiveness; inattention; negligence; <as>as, many
mistakes proceed from <ex>inadvertence</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Inadvertency</qex>, or lack of attendance to the sense and
intention of our prayers.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An effect of inattention; a result of carelessness;
an oversight, mistake, or fault from negligence.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The productions of a great genius, with many lapses an
<qex>inadvertencies</qex>, are infinitely preferable to works of an
inferior kind of author which are scrupulously exact.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Inattention; heedlessness; carelessness;
negligence; thoughtlessness. See <er>Inattention</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inadvertent</ent>⟦br⟧
